README for comp 'sedm'.

***  What is sedm? *** 

The comp 'sedm' emulates sink EDM orbiting.

*** What is EDM? *** 
EDM is a machining method that removes microscopic bits of the workpiece using electrical sparks.
(EDM is a non-traditonal machining method classified as  electrothermal machining)

*** What is sink EDM? *** 
Sink EDM is the variant used to make molds.
(unlike WEDM which is to make dies.)

Sink EDM uses tools with 3D shapes. 
In sink EDM, neither the tool nor work rotate.
(so sink EDM is not like milling or lathe work)

In sink EDM the tool 'sinks' into the work.
As the tool advances, the work material closest to the tool is removed.
As the work material is removed, the tool advances.
The cavity produced _reflects_ the tool shape.

If the tool looked like the letters 'EDW' then the cavity would look like 'EDM'

*** What is Orbiting? *** 
A way to simplify manufacturing the tools.
The 'orbiting' is eccentrically moving the tool to enlarge the cavity.


*** Tools are 3D shapes smaller than the created part *** 
Mold cavities ae larger than the tool. 
Larger by the length of the spark and the radius of orbiting.

The spark length ( Over-burn) is proportional to the spark's energy.
(Current * Duration * Discharge Voltage )
( read the above as 'watt-seconds' or )

Sparks make craters in the work surface.
Sparks with more energy make larger craters and have longer sparks.
Sparks with less energy make shallower craters and have shorter sparks.

Consider a tool at rest in a cavity that was 'roughed out'.
To refine the surface, the power would be reduced.
But the new spark length will not reach the work.
The tool needs to be larger or be orbited.
Orbiting make the tool act larger by moving the tool closer to the wok.


*** Tools can use many spark lengths *** 
To produce a mold cavity, 
more than 1 energy is used.
There is a concept of Rougher, Pr-Finisher and Finisher power settings.

The sedm comp extends this idea to 10 or more power stages.

*** Many power settings minimizes wear, and improves surface finish ***
Each stage is designed to refine the surface with minimum tool wear.

Tool wear increases as energy decreases.
It is necessary to work as little as possible (at low energy.
The energy is kep high(er) to get the most work without wear.

A molding surface is smooth enough to shine.
A molded part will not eject well if the surface is rough.
Surfaces produced by EDM usually do not shine. 
The cavity will usually be  polished after EDM.

The power settings in the supplied tables leave 'pointing stock.
The 'polishing stock is a very few microns, so polishing is fast.


*** Orbiting allows a single sized tool to make many sized cavities *** 
The sink EDM process traditionally used different sized tools.
The tools were called Rougher, Pre-finishers and Finishers.
Each used different energy settings.

It is difficult to make different sized tools with the same center.

Look at an RJ45 connector and image making 3 tools.
They must be smaller than the drawing by 0.15mm, 0.100mm, 0.075 mm.
All these tools must have the same center (the tools can be exchanged)

Orbiting will allow single 0.15mm tool do the work of all 3 sized tools.

Orbiting removes the 'many sizes' issue by moving the tool.
The motion is pattern extending from center.
The pattern is called an orbit.


*** How to use sedm comp *** 
The comp gets needed data from Mcodes an Etable files.
The comp execution is a state machine.
This method requires each state gets completed advancing to next state.
The state machine expects data in the order seen in example.ngc .

The sedm comp is mot difficult to use.
Most of the coding is entering P and Q values for Mcodes.

*** Begin with a drawing *** 
Find the  Fp: (frontal projection)

Fp is the cross sectional area of the tool at the 'parting line'.
Fp is like a birds shadow.

The exact area is not important.
The task is to select a size from a list.
( 3x3mm , ... 25x50mm,...up to 100x100mm) 

*** Use cheat-sheets to select Etable, and find UNS *** 
The file cheatsheet.pdf will help you plan your work.
It lists the UNS to make your tool.
UNS is 'under size per side'.

*** Pairing ***
This step asks you what the tool and work materials are.
This is is called Pairing.
The cheat sheet will guide you to a suitable Etable file.
The Etable file is a list of power settings.
E tables are sorted by Fp and Pairing.

( TOD O make copper to steel chheatsjeets )

Please refer to the  now.

In the cheat sheet look for the closest Fp.

The cheat sheet lists 4 grades of graphite.
These grades are 25 20 9 and 4.
25 means extremely fine grain size.
20 means very fine.
9 is standard.
4 is large particle size.

Large work uses graphite with larger particles.
Smaller work use material with smaller grain size.

Larger grain material will not allow fine detail.
Smaller grain material can be used for very fine details.

Large grain material costs less.
Small grain material costs more.

The 25 grade is very dense and 20 less so.
The column 9 is acceptable for general work.
and 4 is only used for heavy roughing of large castings.

cheat sheet #1 us for cutting with flush holes thru the tool.
cheat sheet #2 is for without thru flush.
cheat Sheet #2 relies on external flushing and 'Peck EDM'.
(Peck aka 'Jump)


Use the cheat sheet to choose your Fp and an Etable.
Open the Etable file in a text editor and find the UNS value.


*** Choose the Tool Axis and  select the Plane *** 
If the cavity is cut , the the Tool Axis will be Z.
And circles will be in the X Y plane.

Linuxcnc has 3 PLANE codes, G17, G18, G19.
Each define a tool axis.
Each defines a plane dor circular interpolation.

A cavity cut forwards ( away from the user) is G18.
The Tool Axis is Y, and circles are in X Z .

Select the Tool Axis by adding the correct PLANE code in the ngc file


*** sedm can cut in many directions *** 
The sedm comp will cut Up Down Left Right Forwards and Backwards.


*** Make your tool *** 
Make your tool smaller than the drawing  by UNS.
This reduction is 2D, so,only reduce X and Y for a G17 Z tool.
Do not reduce the tool length.

*** Register the actual UNS *** 
Measure the tool to find the .

You wanted the tool to be UNS smaller,
but its OK to be smaller  ( larger is not allowed).
The sedm comp can adapt the orbiting to allow 'extra UNS'/

If the MeasuredUNS > UNS, then you are not finished making the tool.
Go back and grind some more ;-)


*** Prepare an M code M160 *** 
Use this format:
   M160 P<Etable number Q<measured UNS>
   
   Eg   M160 P34 Q0.508


*** Get Print Depth and location *** 
Find the cavity depth and a reference for that depth. 
(How deep, measured from where)

You will set a reference position using G10L2 P1 X(val> Y<val> Z<val>
The sedm motion will be relative to that datum.


*** R plane, where power is turned on *** 
The R plane is a small distance 'above' the work.
EDM requires starting with the tool not touching the work.
For R plane values, large values waste time, small values can be scary.

Using the Full Depth and R Plane values to fill M162 data.
   M162 P<Full Depth> Q<R plane>
   
   Eg  M162 P-1.304 Q1.0


*** Select Orbit Type and   *** 

Orbit types supplied in sedm are Circular and Square.
Use 0 for Circular. 1 for Square.

(In the future more orbit types can be aded)
( I have written Spherical, Undercut back-taper Sub-gate and diggetydog )


*** Difference in resulting form: Circular versus Square orbiting ***
A right angle corner will produce a radius of UNS in the work.
The same corner will create a radius of the E table's last NR’s RAD value.

If FWD, the tool advances to the next tuple in the list of eoffsets.
The data is given to the axis eoffsets pins.

If HOLD:
There is no motion. 
The sparking process continues and eventually changes pt FWD or BWD.
In the meantime the the tool keeps sparking.
Good sparking will enlarge the GAP distance and change the gap voltage.


If the evaluation is BWD:  
BWD causes DETOURS:
A new path will be generated to move the tool away from stock.

*** Detours are essential to sink EDM *** 
Watch detours in action.
Run the example.ngc file.
Use the Y view and zoom in to watch. 

The bore wigl will look like a coiled spring.
The orbit entry will be a diagonal motion down and away from center.
The orbit will appear as a horizontal motion.
(You are looking at the edge of a disk)
The tool tip will travel left and right.

*** Notice the  *** 

The tool is moving horizontally but with many tiny jumps.

Those 'jumps' are detours. 

The DRO will show they are only a few microns long.

You are seeing only part of the detour.
You see whats used to get the 'gap voltage' to agree with the target.
The entire detour extends back to the start pony.

A BWD event moves the tool away from the planned path.
A FWD event moves towards preplanned path.


*** Interaction with sedm *** 

*** Peck EDM aka  *** 
Turn the JUMP on and off, using the checkbox.
The tool will cut for the E table's  ET value.
The tool will retract for the AJD value.
Jump remains on until the checkbox is cleared.

*** PEEK RESUME QUIT *** 
Imagine you want to examine the tool or look into the cavity.

Try The PEEK button while cutting.

The cutting power is removed,
and the tool returns to its start point

After inspection , you can press RESUME or QUIT.


*** Other sources of information ***
I suggest you look at the Entegris EDM Graphite manual.
The Mersen Graphite documents.
Toyo Tanso graphite documents.
(These are not an endorsements, sometimes tech data is from a salesman)

Also look for OelhHeld's book on dielectric fluids.

Ard anything printed by the ISEM and JSEM.

You should develop a mental image of what goes on in a cut.
You should keep a journal.


Have fun. Post questions and suggestion and bugs.
